  "doc_id": "61304",
  "text": "Hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection is another common chronic viral infection, with estimates as high as 350 million chronically infected humans [CITATION_1] . Bility and colleagues (78) recently developed a humanized mouse model with both a human immune system and human liver cells, named the A2/NSG-hu HSC/Hep humanized mouse model, to study the pathogenesis of HBV infection. Following HBV infection, the mice developed persistent HBV infection as well as chronic hepatitis and liver fibrosis [CITATION_2] . The liver disease was associated with a high level of infiltrating human macrophages with a M2-like activation phenotype [CITATION_3] . Similarly, M2-like macrophage accumulation was seen in chronic HBV-infected patients, and M2-like macrophage induction in the liver was associated with accelerated liver fibrosis and necrosis in patients with acute HBV-induced liver failure [CITATION_4] , suggesting a role for M2 macrophages in persistent HBV infection. Additionally, patients with acute HBV infection had increased serum levels of arginase, and this serum inhibited IFN-γ production by CD8 + T cells [CITATION_5] . Das et al. (80) also found decreased l-arginine levels in the circulation of chronic HBV patients with marked liver inflammation (>100 ALT) and increased arginase activity in liver extracts taken directly ex vivo from patients with chronic HBV compared with those from patients with other types of liver pathology [CITATION_6] . They further showed that CD8 + T cells from chronic HBV patients, regardless of their antigen specificity, exhibited less IL-2 but not IFN-γ or TNF-α production and impaired proliferation following TCR-dependent stimulation, indicating an aberrant antiviral T cell response in chronic HBV infection [CITATION_7] . In the A2/NSG-hu HSC/Hep humanized mouse model, HBV-infected mice had impaired liver T cell responses, and M2 macrophages were associated with T cells in the liver [CITATION_8] . Expression of the TCR signaling molecule CD3ζ was reduced in both peripheral and intrahepatic CD8 + T cells from chronic HBV patients; similarly, CD28 was also downregulated on CD8 + T cells from high viral load HBV patients [CITATION_9] . Downregulation of the CD3ζ molecule has previously been shown to occur in the arginine-depleted tumor microenvironment. Consistent with this, in vitro transfection of CD3ζ and CD28 restored IL-2 production and supplementation of l-arginine partially restored CD3ζ expression and T cell proliferation [CITATION_10] . These data suggest a role www.frontiersin.org for arginase activity and arginine depletion in the impairment of anti-HBV T cells functions.",
